"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 4–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2kings-4-5.py

Ch4: Four miracles of Elisha — widow's oil, Shunammite's son (promised and raised),
     stew purified, loaves multiplied. Each is a type of Christ's works.
Ch5: Naaman's healing — the paradigmatic Gentile conversion narrative;
     Gehazi's sin — the Judas/elder-son type.

Key typological connections:
- 4:1-7: widow's oil multiplied → John 6 (provision from nothing); grace fills every vessel
- 4:17: barren Shunammite bears son → Annunciation pattern (Gen 18:14; Luke 1:31)
- 4:34: Elisha lies over dead child → resurrection type; Heb 11:35
- 4:43-44: 20 loaves feed 100 with leftovers → Mark 6:37-44 (feeding of 5000)
- 5:1-14: Naaman (Luke 4:27) — Gentile outsider receives grace denied to insiders
- 5:10-12: simple Jordan washing offends pride → 1 Cor 1:23 (stumbling block/foolishness)
- 5:15: 'no God in all the earth except in Israel' → Gentile confession; Eph 2:12-13
- 5:17-18: mule-loads of earth / Rimmon problem → John 4:21; Acts 15 pastoral pattern
- 5:20-27: Gehazi's greed → Judas type; Luke 15:28 (elder son resentment of grace)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>A widow from the sons of the prophets cries out to Elisha: her husband is dead, a creditor is coming to take her two children as slaves. The widow of a prophet — the most vulnerable position in the prophetic community — is the one YHWH addresses through Elisha. The pattern of divine attention to the most marginalized (widow, orphan, stranger — Exod 22:21-24; Deut 10:18) is realized in Elisha&rsquo;s ministry. Jesus&rsquo;s citation in Luke 4:26 of Elijah&rsquo;s widow at Zarephath establishes the canonical framework: the prophets&rsquo; provision miracles are specifically directed at those whom the social order has failed. The widow&rsquo;s cry (<em>ṣāʿaq</em>) is the covenantal distress-cry — the same word used of Israel in Egypt (Exod 3:7).</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;What can I do for you? Tell me — what do you have in the house?&rdquo; Elisha begins not with a grand gesture but with a question about existing resources. The one jar of oil (<em>ʾăsûk šemen</em>) is the starting point; YHWH does not create from absolute nothing in these provision miracles but multiplies what the recipient already holds. John 2:6-7: Jesus does not manufacture water from nothing — he transforms water already present in the jars. The principle: bring what you have; YHWH multiplies it. Mark 6:38: &ldquo;How many loaves do you have? Go and see.&rdquo;</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Go and borrow vessels from all your neighbors — empty containers, and do not get too few.&rdquo; The only limit on the miracle is the number of vessels. The widow is to gather empty vessels — <em>kēlîm rêqîm</em> — as many as possible. The instruction &ldquo;do not get too few&rdquo; sets the terms: the provision will fill exactly as many containers as are brought. The limiting factor is not the supply of oil (YHWH&rsquo;s provision) but the capacity of the receiver. Jesus: &ldquo;Ask, and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you&rdquo; (Matt 7:7) — the asking is the vessel-gathering; the provision is as large as the faith that seeks.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Elisha instructs the widow to go inside with her sons, shut the door, and pour. The privacy of the miracle — she and her sons shut in together — protects the sacred act from spectacle. The Incarnation is characterized by this same privacy: born in a manger, announced to shepherds, raised in an obscure village. The provision comes in hiddenness; faith acts in the unseen space before the miracle becomes visible to others.</p>",
    "5": "<p>She pours and the oil multiplies as long as there are vessels. The act of faith precedes the visible provision — she pours into the first vessel without seeing the oil multiply; only in the pouring does the miracle occur. Heb 11:1: &ldquo;faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen&rdquo; — the widow is filling vessels with oil she has not yet seen, acting on the word alone. The multiplication is not instantaneous and complete but incremental, requiring continued active faith.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;When the containers were all full, she said to her son, &lsquo;Bring me another vessel.&rsquo; He said, &lsquo;There are no more.&rsquo; And the oil stopped.&rdquo; The oil stops precisely when the last vessel is full — not a drop is wasted, not a vessel is left unfilled. The provision is precisely calibrated to the capacity brought. John 6:12: at the feeding of the 5000, Jesus says &ldquo;gather up the leftover fragments, that nothing may be lost&rdquo; — the same precision of divine economy. The miracle is not abundance beyond all capacity but sufficiency for every vessel available.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Go, sell the oil and pay your debt. You and your sons can live on the rest.&rdquo; The miracle has two stages: (1) pay the debt that threatened to enslave the children; (2) live on the remainder. The provision solves the legal problem (debt/slavery) first, then provides for ongoing life. The order mirrors the gospel: Christ&rsquo;s death pays the debt of sin that held humanity in bondage (Col 2:13-14: &ldquo;having forgiven us all our trespasses, having canceled the record of debt&rdquo;), and the remaining provision is the life that follows redemption.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Shunammite woman is introduced as wealthy (<em>ʾiššāh gᵉḏôlāh</em> — &ldquo;great woman&rdquo;) and hospitable: she pressed Elisha to eat whenever he passed. The wealthy woman who provides for the prophet is the OT hospitality pattern that Jesus will invoke: &ldquo;Whoever receives a prophet because he is a prophet will receive a prophet&rsquo;s reward&rdquo; (Matt 10:41). The Shunammite&rsquo;s hospitality to Elisha, though she does not yet know she will need anything from him, is the prerequisite for the miracle she will receive.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;I am sure this man who keeps passing by is a holy man of God (<em>ʾîš ʾelōhîm qāḏôš</em>).&rdquo; The Shunammite identifies Elisha as <em>qāḏôš</em> — set apart, consecrated — through sustained observation of his conduct. The recognition of holiness by a discerning layperson is a significant NT theme: the disciples&rsquo; gradual recognition of who Jesus is (Matt 16:16: &ldquo;You are the Christ, the Son of the living God&rdquo;), and Peter&rsquo;s statement after the miraculous catch of fish: &ldquo;Depart from me, for I am a sinful man, O Lord&rdquo; (Luke 5:8).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The roof chamber built for Elisha — bed, table, chair, lamp — is a model of material provision for the servant of YHWH. The four furnishings (bed for rest, table for food, chair for sitting, lamp for light) represent the complete provision of the body&rsquo;s needs. Matt 10:10-11: &ldquo;the laborer deserves his food... whatever house you enter, stay there.&rdquo; The church&rsquo;s provision for its ministers has its OT type in the Shunammite&rsquo;s chamber.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Elisha comes and rests in the chamber — the rest of the servant is the fruit of the hospitality. The provision is accepted without excessive formality; the man of God uses what is given for its purpose. The simplicity of the divine servant who accepts provision and uses it appropriately.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Elisha speaks to the Shunammite through Gehazi — the intermediary communication. The use of a servant as intermediary reflects the formal distance between a great prophet and a great woman; Elisha maintains appropriate boundaries. The distance is overcome when crisis comes (v27: she grabs Elisha&rsquo;s feet directly).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elisha asks what can be done for her — offering to use his prophetic connections (&ldquo;Should I speak a word to the king or to the commander of the army?&rdquo;). She answers: &ldquo;I dwell among my own people.&rdquo; The Shunammite does not ask for status or political access — she is at home where she is. Her contentment with her own people is a form of covenant faithfulness: she is not reaching for more than she has. The one who is content with her inheritance does not grasp; she will receive what she has not grasped.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Gehazi identifies the one lack: she has no son, and her husband is old. The barrenness that has gone unspoken — she did not ask; she did not petition; she simply served the prophet. The grace that gives what was not requested. Luke 1:30-31: &ldquo;Do not be afraid, Mary, for you have found favor with God. And behold, you will conceive in your womb and bear a son.&rdquo; The Annunciation echoes this structure: the woman who did not ask receives the most significant gift.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Elisha has her called and she stands in the doorway. The spatial positioning — she stands at the threshold, between inside (her domestic world) and outside (the prophetic word) — marks the moment of encounter between the ordinary and the extraordinary.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;About this time next year you will hold a son in your arms.&rdquo; The wording echoes Gen 18:14 almost exactly: <em>kāʿēt ḥayyāh</em> — &ldquo;when the time revives/at the living time.&rdquo; The Sarah-Shunammite connection is deliberate: the barren woman who receives a son by prophetic word is the recurring type of the unexpected divine gift of life. The Shunammite&rsquo;s response — &ldquo;No, my lord, man of God — do not lie to your servant&rdquo; — echoes Sarah&rsquo;s laughter (Gen 18:12). Both women resist the word before receiving it. The resistance is not disqualifying; YHWH fulfills his promise through the disbelieving recipient as much as the believing one.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Shunammite conceives and bears a son — the word is fulfilled exactly as spoken, at exactly the time specified. The pattern of prophetic fulfillment: the word given is the word accomplished. Isa 55:11: &ldquo;my word... shall not return to me empty, but it shall accomplish that which I purpose and shall succeed in the thing for which I sent it.&rdquo; The specific fulfillment of the specific word is the OT&rsquo;s ongoing demonstration of YHWH&rsquo;s reliability.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The child grows and goes out to the reapers — his life follows the normal course of a child who has been miraculously given. The miracle of origin does not exempt him from the ordinary rhythms of life. Jesus: &ldquo;he grew and became strong, filled with wisdom&rdquo; (Luke 2:40) — the miraculously born child lives within the ordinary conditions of creaturely existence.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;My head! My head!&rdquo; — sudden and unexplained illness overtakes the gift-child. The narrative moves from the miracle of birth to the crisis of death with stark economy. The gift of grace is not a guarantee against suffering; the promised child still dies. The greatest promises of God are fulfilled through death, not around it. The typological significance: the miracle child must die before the greater miracle of his restoration.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The child sits on his mother&rsquo;s lap until noon, then dies. The intimacy of the death — in his mother&rsquo;s arms — and its timing (noon, the middle of the day, the point of maximum light) make the death more stark, not less. The death of the gift-child in the mother&rsquo;s arms: Mary at the foot of the cross holds a different version of this grief — the promised son who dies in her presence.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The mother takes the dead child, lays him on the prophet&rsquo;s bed, and shuts the door. She places the dead son specifically on Elisha&rsquo;s bed — the bed provided by her hospitality, now used as the locus of the miracle she will demand. The act is interpretively charged: she is putting the problem where the solution lives. She does not despair; she acts. Her action embodies a theology: the death of the gift-child is a problem for the man of God to solve, not a fate to accept.</p>",
    "22": "<p>She sends word to her husband for a servant and donkey — normal domestic preparations — while saying nothing about the child&rsquo;s death. The reserve is not deception but purposeful silence: she is going to the man of God with her problem; there is nothing her husband can do. The discernment to distinguish what a spouse can provide from what only the prophet can address.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;Why go to him today? It is neither a new moon nor the Sabbath.&rdquo; The husband assumes prophetic visits are only appropriate on designated holy days — the institutional understanding of access to God. The Shunammite&rsquo;s answer, <em>šālôm</em> — &ldquo;it is well&rdquo; — is a statement of faith, not fact: it is not yet well, but she speaks as if it will be. &ldquo;Do not be anxious about anything&rdquo; (Phil 4:6) — her <em>šālôm</em>-answer in the face of crisis is the OT form of the peace that passes understanding.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;Drive on and do not slow down unless I tell you.&rdquo; The urgency of the journey to the man of God in crisis. The same urgency governs the friends who carry their paralyzed companion to Jesus, tearing open the roof (Mark 2:4) — the crisis creates extraordinary measures to reach the one who can address it.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Elisha sees her coming from a distance and says to Gehazi: &ldquo;Look — it is the Shunammite!&rdquo; The prophetic recognition at a distance — Elisha perceives her before she speaks. Jesus sees Nathanael &ldquo;under the fig tree&rdquo; before they meet (John 1:48); he knows the Samaritan woman&rsquo;s history before she tells him (John 4:17-18). The servant of YHWH perceives what the natural eye does not yet see.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;Run to meet her and ask: Is it well with you? With your husband? With the child?&rdquo; — and she answers each question: <em>šālôm</em>. Three times <em>šālôm</em>. The triple answer of peace in the moment of maximum grief is one of the most theologically dense moments in the narrative. She does not lie; she speaks the eschatological reality she has come to demand. Cf. the risen Jesus&rsquo;s triple greeting of peace: &ldquo;Peace be with you&rdquo; (John 20:19, 21, 26) — in the moment when death has been experienced, peace is the word of the one who has addressed it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>She catches Elisha&rsquo;s feet — the posture of petition and distress (cf. Matt 28:9: the women clasp Jesus&rsquo;s feet at the resurrection). Gehazi tries to push her away — the disciple who protects the master from the desperate suppliant (Mark 10:13-14: disciples rebuking those bringing children; Jesus: &ldquo;Let the children come to me&rdquo;). Elisha overrules Gehazi: &ldquo;let her alone, for she is in bitter distress.&rdquo; The master&rsquo;s openness to the desperate over the disciple&rsquo;s gatekeeping.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;Did I ask my lord for a son? Did I not say, Do not give me false hope?&rdquo; The Shunammite holds Elisha to account for the gift he gave. Her accusation is covenantally appropriate: he promised; the promise-child died; he is responsible to complete what he began. The boldness of faith that confronts the prophet with his own word. Cf. the Syrophoenician woman (Matt 15:27: &ldquo;Yes, Lord, yet even the dogs eat the crumbs that fall from their master&rsquo;s table&rdquo;) — the persistent faith that will not accept a no. The prayer that presses God with his own promises is the OT&rsquo;s model of covenant prayer.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Elisha sends Gehazi with the staff to lay on the child&rsquo;s face. The staff as instrument of prophetic power: Moses&rsquo;s staff in Exodus; Elijah&rsquo;s cloak. The proxy mission fails (v31): there was &ldquo;no sound and no sign of life.&rdquo; The instrument without the person cannot accomplish what only the personal presence achieves. Gehazi&rsquo;s failed staff anticipates the teaching that the works of Christ cannot be replicated by those who use his name as a formula without his presence (Matt 7:22-23: &ldquo;Lord, Lord, did we not cast out demons in your name... I never knew you&rdquo;).</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;As the LORD lives and as you yourself live, I will not leave you.&rdquo; The Shunammite refuses to be satisfied with the proxy; she requires Elisha&rsquo;s personal presence. Her insistence mirrors Ruth&rsquo;s oath to Naomi (Ruth 1:16-17) and the disciples&rsquo; post-resurrection insistence on the bodily presence of the risen Christ (&ldquo;Unless I see the mark of the nails,&rdquo; John 20:25 — Thomas refuses the proxy report). The resurrection requires the personal, bodily presence of the risen one; no messenger or report is sufficient.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Gehazi&rsquo;s staff produces no response — the child neither speaks nor wakes. The failure of the instrument without the person is confirmed. Elisha is told and goes himself. The principle: no technique, formula, or instrument of grace can substitute for the personal presence and action of the giver of life.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Elisha arrives and sees the child lying dead on his bed — the same bed where the child was conceived through his prophetic word. The child of the miracle lies dead in the place of the miracle. The connection between promise and fulfillment, between the word of life given and the death that interrupts it, is spatial: the bed is the same. Jesus is buried in a borrowed tomb — the new creation&rsquo;s first act happens in the place of death.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Elisha shuts the door on himself and the child and prays to YHWH. The privacy of the resurrection act — no witnesses — is the pattern of Elijah at Zarephath (1 Kgs 17:20) and Jesus at the raising of Jairus&rsquo;s daughter (Mark 5:40: he puts them all outside). The death and the resurrection are not public spectacle but intimate encounter between the prophet and YHWH, mediated through the body of the dead child.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Elisha lies on the child — &ldquo;mouth to his mouth, eyes to his eyes, hands to his hands&rdquo; — and the child&rsquo;s body grows warm. The physical act of superimposition — the living body over the dead one — is a type of the Incarnation&rsquo;s logic: the living God assumes the full form of human death (Phil 2:7-8: &ldquo;emptying himself, taking the form of a servant, being born in the likeness of men... becoming obedient to the point of death&rdquo;) in order to bring life from within the dead condition. Elijah did the same (1 Kgs 17:21); Jesus goes further — not merely touching death from outside but entering it completely. &ldquo;Since therefore the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things, that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death&rdquo; (Heb 2:14).</p>",
    "35": "<p>Elisha rises, walks back and forth, lies over the child again — the child sneezes seven times and opens his eyes. The seven sneezes mark covenantal completeness (seven as the number of covenant perfection); the return of bodily function is total. The resurrection of the dead: not resuscitation but restoration. Heb 11:35: &ldquo;Women received back their dead by resurrection&rdquo; — the Shunammite is the second in the OT&rsquo;s resurrection chain (after the Zarephath widow).</p>",
    "36": "<p>Elisha calls Gehazi: &ldquo;Call the Shunammite.&rdquo; The one who sent her away with a proxy is now the one who calls her to receive back the living child. The circle of the servant&rsquo;s inadequacy is closed by the master&rsquo;s completion of the work. &ldquo;Take up your son&rdquo; — the return of the gift. Mary Magdalene at the tomb is told: &ldquo;Go and tell&rdquo; — the resurrection is announced by the one who witnessed it to the ones who most need to hear it.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The Shunammite falls at Elisha&rsquo;s feet, bows to the ground, takes up her son, and goes out. The triple movement — fall, bow, take — is the physical expression of gratitude for the impossible. The resurrection of her son cost her nothing; she gave hospitality and received life from death. The gospel logic: the gift of life is disproportionate to any human act of service that precedes it.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Elisha returns to Gilgal during a famine — the place of Israel&rsquo;s first encampment in Canaan (Josh 4:19-20) becomes the place where the sons of the prophets gather and Elisha provides for them. The famine context connects this provision miracle to the Carmel drought provisions of the Elijah cycle and to the wilderness manna: YHWH&rsquo;s servants do not lack even when the land does.</p>",
    "39": "<p>One of the young prophets gathers wild gourds (<em>paqquʿōt śādeh</em>) — an unidentified wild plant, apparently poisonous — and puts them in the stew without knowing their danger. The innocence of the error does not prevent the harm: the stew becomes deadly. Death enters through well-intentioned ignorance. Gen 3: the fatal fruit is taken without full understanding of its cost. The human condition: we do not always know what we are putting into the pot.</p>",
    "40": "<p>&ldquo;Man of God, there is death in the pot!&rdquo; — the recognition of the deadly ingredient comes only after tasting. The prophet is appealed to immediately; the source of the problem is known but the solution is not. Death that has entered through ignorance requires the prophetic intervention that knowledge alone cannot provide.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Elisha throws flour into the pot and declares it safe. The flour is the antidote to the wild gourds — the cultivated grain that neutralizes the wild poison. The flour-type: Elijah&rsquo;s flour (1 Kgs 17:12-14), Elisha&rsquo;s flour here, the flour of the meal offering — the grain that sustains life in contrast to the wild that destroys it. Jesus: &ldquo;I am the bread of life&rdquo; (John 6:35) — the cultivated, provided bread that counters the death that enters through the wild grasping of what was not meant to be eaten.</p>",
    "42": "<p>A man from Baal-shalishah brings twenty barley loaves baked from the firstfruits and fresh grain in a sack. The <em>bikkûrîm</em> (firstfruits) offering is given to the man of God — the normal provision for prophets and priests (Num 18:12-13). The bringing of firstfruits to the servant of YHWH is an act of covenant faithfulness during the famine: this man has honored the firstfruits obligation even when food is scarce.</p>",
    "43": "<p>&ldquo;How can I set this before a hundred men?&rdquo; Gehazi&rsquo;s objection mirrors exactly the disciples&rsquo; objection at the feeding of the 5000 (Mark 6:37: &ldquo;Shall we go and buy two hundred denarii worth of bread?&rdquo;; John 6:7: &ldquo;Two hundred denarii worth of bread would not be enough&rdquo;). The servant&rsquo;s logic is arithmetic; the prophet&rsquo;s logic is covenantal. The same word is used: &ldquo;Give it to the people that they may eat — for thus says the LORD: &lsquo;They shall eat and have some left over.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>",
    "44": "<p>&ldquo;He set it before them. They ate and had some left over, according to the word of the LORD.&rdquo; The word of YHWH is the operative agent: the multiplication happens through the word, not through any natural process. The three-element structure (set before / ate / had some left over) is exactly replicated in the feeding of the 5000 (Mark 6:42-43: &ldquo;they all ate and were satisfied; and they took up twelve baskets full of broken pieces&rdquo;). Jesus is not merely performing a similar miracle — he is consciously enacting and completing the type. John 6:14: &ldquo;This is indeed the Prophet who is to come into the world!&rdquo; — the crowd sees the Elisha-type fulfilled in Jesus.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Naaman is introduced with maximum social prestige: commander of the Aramean army, great man (<em>gāḏôl</em>), highly regarded (<em>nᵉśûʾ pānîm</em> — literally &ldquo;of lifted face&rdquo; — honored by his master), victorious in battle — YHWH himself is said to have given him the victories. And then: <em>mᵉṣōrāʿ</em> — he was a leper. The structure is the ancient rhetorical form for tragic irony: greatness exhaustively catalogued, then undercut by a single condition that all the greatness cannot address. Wealth, honor, power, military success — and leprosy. Luke 4:27: Jesus cites Naaman specifically as the paradigm case of grace going to unexpected outsiders. The commander of Israel&rsquo;s enemy army becomes the first recorded Gentile recipient of covenantal healing.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A little girl from Israel — captured in an Aramean raid, serving Naaman&rsquo;s wife — carries the word that will heal him. She is unnamed, enslaved, from the enemy people, and a child. The concentric circles of marginalization are total. Yet she is the person through whom the redemptive word travels. 1 Cor 1:27-29: &ldquo;God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise; God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong; God chose what is low and despised in the world.&rdquo; The word that heals Naaman comes from the lowest person in his household.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;If only my lord were before the prophet who is in Samaria! He would cure him of his leprosy.&rdquo; The girl&rsquo;s testimony is confident and specific: the prophet who is in Samaria can heal. She does not say &ldquo;I think,&rdquo; or &ldquo;perhaps.&rdquo; Her faith in Elisha&rsquo;s capacity is unqualified. Acts 8:4: &ldquo;those who were scattered went about preaching the word&rdquo; — the captives of the dispersion become the missionaries to the Gentiles. The Samaritan woman at the well (John 4:39: &ldquo;many Samaritans believed because of the woman&rsquo;s testimony&rdquo;) is the NT version of the same pattern: a woman&rsquo;s witness brings outsiders to the one who heals.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Naaman reports the girl&rsquo;s word to the king of Aram — from slave girl to king in one step. The redemptive word travels upward through the social hierarchy by the force of its content, not the status of its carrier. The king of Aram takes the girl&rsquo;s testimony seriously enough to dispatch a diplomatic mission. Even power listens when desperation is great enough.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The king sends Naaman with ten talents of silver, six thousand shekels of gold, and ten changes of clothing — enormous wealth intended to purchase the healing. The gift-package attempts to commodify what is freely given. Acts 8:18-19: Simon Magus offers money for the gift of the Spirit. The pattern of those who approach grace as a transaction is consistent: they assume divine favor can be obtained by what is brought rather than by what is received. The wealth Naaman carries will be irrelevant to his healing and a temptation to Gehazi (v20-27).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The king of Aram writes to the king of Israel: &ldquo;I have sent my servant Naaman to you, that you may cure him of his leprosy.&rdquo; The diplomatic channel bypasses the prophet and addresses the king — the institutional approach to grace. The king of Israel is not the healing agent; the prophet is. Approaching God through official channels (political, institutional, hereditary) instead of through the one God has appointed is a recurring human error. John 14:6: &ldquo;No one comes to the Father except through me.&rdquo;</p>",
    "7": "<p>The king of Israel tears his clothes: &ldquo;Am I God, to give death and life, that this man sends to me to cure a man of his leprosy?&rdquo; The king&rsquo;s question is theologically correct — only God can heal leprosy — but practically wrong, because the prophet who speaks for that God is in his kingdom. His tearing of garments misreads the diplomatic letter as a pretext for war; he cannot imagine that YHWH could heal through his prophet. The institutional leader who cannot see the prophetic resource in his own land.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elisha hears of the king&rsquo;s distress and sends word: &ldquo;Let him come to me, that he may know there is a prophet in Israel.&rdquo; The purpose of the healing is stated explicitly: <em>wəyēḏaʿ kî yēš nāḇîʾ bəyiśrāʾēl</em> — the knowledge of YHWH&rsquo;s presence in Israel through his prophet. John 20:31: &ldquo;these are written so that you may believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God.&rdquo; The miracles are not ends in themselves but revelation — they create knowledge of who YHWH is and where he acts.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Naaman comes with his horses and chariots — the full military display of a great man — and stands at the door of Elisha&rsquo;s house. The power and pomp of the Aramean general before the threshold of the prophet&rsquo;s ordinary house: the great man waiting at the ordinary door is the reversal of expected social power. Jesus: &ldquo;Behold, I stand at the door and knock&rdquo; (Rev 3:20) — the divine one waiting at the human door is the ultimate reversal.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Elisha does not come out but sends a messenger: &ldquo;Go and wash in the Jordan seven times, and your flesh will be restored, and you shall be clean.&rdquo; The instruction has three qualities that give offense: (1) Elisha does not come in person; (2) the instruction is insultingly simple; (3) the Jordan — an inferior Israelite river — is specified. The simplicity of the gospel has always been its stumbling block. The means of salvation — faith in the crucified, baptism into his death — appears foolish and inadequate to those who expect something commensurate with their need.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Naaman is angry: &ldquo;I expected him to come out to me in person, call on the name of the LORD his God, wave his hand over the place, and cure me of my leprosy.&rdquo; Naaman has a detailed script for how the healing should work: the prophet appears, invokes YHWH, performs a dramatic gesture. What he expects is a theurgic ritual — the manipulation of divine power by a qualified specialist using proper technique. 1 Cor 1:22-23: &ldquo;Jews demand signs and Greeks seek wisdom, but we preach Christ crucified.&rdquo; The cross is foolishness because it refuses the script of power and wisdom; Naaman&rsquo;s rage at the Jordan instruction is the Gentile form of the same offense.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;Are not Abana and Pharpar, the rivers of Damascus, better than all the waters of Israel? Could I not wash in them and be clean?&rdquo; The question is perfectly logical by every natural standard: the Abana and Pharpar (Barada and Awaj rivers) are indeed clear, full rivers; the Jordan is murkier and less impressive. But the healing is not in the water&rsquo;s quality — it is in the word attached to it. The sacramental principle: the efficacy of baptism is not in the water&rsquo;s chemistry but in the Word of God that commands and promises. Luther: &ldquo;it is not the water that does these things, but the Word of God which is in and with the water.&rdquo;</p>",
    "13": "<p>His servants appeal: &ldquo;My father (<em>ʾāḇî</em>), if the prophet had told you to do something great, would you not have done it? How much more, when he says to you, Wash and be clean?&rdquo; The servants&rsquo; logic is the logic of the lesser to the greater. Naaman would have performed any dramatic, costly requirement — why refuse the simple one? The pride that can bear the great sacrifice but cannot bear the humble act is the characteristic human resistance to grace. John 13:8-9: Peter refuses to have his feet washed, then asks for a full bath — the overcorrection of pride brought low.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;I know that there is no God in all the earth except in Israel.&rdquo; The Gentile confession after healing: the definitive monotheistic acknowledgment from a pagan military commander who came to buy a healing and instead received a revelation. The structure of Naaman&rsquo;s conversion — encounter with a captive witness (v3), dramatic encounter with the prophet, healing through simple obedience, personal confession — is the pattern of Gentile conversion in Acts (cf. Acts 10:34-48: Cornelius; Acts 16:27-34: Philippian jailer). Eph 2:12-13: those who were &ldquo;strangers to the covenants of promise, having no hope and without God in the world&rdquo; are &ldquo;brought near by the blood of Christ.&rdquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;As the LORD lives, before whom I stand, I will receive nothing.&rdquo; Elisha refuses all payment for the healing. The gift of healing that cannot be purchased is the grace that must remain free. Matt 10:8: &ldquo;You received without paying; give without pay.&rdquo; The refusal of payment is itself a proclamation: YHWH&rsquo;s gifts are not for sale. Elisha&rsquo;s refusal contrasts with every commercial religious system then and now; it anticipates Jesus&rsquo;s temple cleansing (Matt 21:12-13) — the house of prayer cannot be a house of commerce.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Naaman requests two mule-loads of Israelite earth to build an altar for YHWH at Damascus — he will worship YHWH only on Israelite soil. The earth-theology is transitional: in the ANE, gods were considered to have territorial jurisdiction; Naaman imports the territory of YHWH&rsquo;s land. The request is simultaneously theologically limited (YHWH still geographically bound in Naaman&rsquo;s mind) and theologically revolutionary (a Gentile worshiping YHWH in his own country). John 4:21-24: Jesus dismantles the territorial theology entirely — &ldquo;the hour is coming when you will worship the Father neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem... true worshipers will worship the Father in spirit and truth.&rdquo; Naaman&rsquo;s two mule-loads of earth point toward the worship that no longer needs any particular soil.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;When my master goes into the house of Rimmon to worship there, leaning on my arm, and I bow myself in the house of Rimmon — when I bow myself in the house of Rimmon, may YHWH pardon your servant in this one matter.&rdquo; The Rimmon problem is the first missionary pastoral dilemma: the Gentile convert who must function in a context of unavoidable idolatry. Naaman is not asking permission to worship Rimmon; he is asking pardon for an unavoidable bodily participation in a ceremony he will not internally affirm. Elisha&rsquo;s &ldquo;go in peace&rdquo; without qualification is remarkable pastoral accommodation. The Apostolic Council (Acts 15) wrestles with the same question: what does the Gentile convert owe to the full Torah? The answer in both cases: not the full burden, but the core of covenantal faith.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;Go in peace.&rdquo; — <em>lēk lᵉšālôm</em>. The word of release given to the healed Gentile. The same word that ends Elijah&rsquo;s encounter with the widow (1 Kgs 17:23: &ldquo;See, your son lives&rdquo;) and will be spoken by Jesus at departures of healing (&ldquo;Your faith has saved you; go in peace,&rdquo; Luke 7:50; 8:48). The <em>šālôm</em> word is the blessing that accompanies those whom YHWH has restored and released.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Gehazi&rsquo;s interior monologue: &ldquo;My master has let this Aramean off too lightly by not accepting from him what he brought.&rdquo; The resentment of grace extended to the outsider — the elder son&rsquo;s reaction when the father throws a feast for the prodigal (Luke 15:28-30: &ldquo;I have served you these many years, and you never gave me a young goat... but when this son of yours came, who has devoured your property with prostitutes, you killed the fattened calf for him&rdquo;). Gehazi&rsquo;s &ldquo;too lightly&rdquo; is the disciple&rsquo;s refusal of the logic of grace: that the gift should be given freely, without extraction.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Gehazi runs after Naaman. When Naaman sees him coming, he steps down from his chariot to meet him — the just-healed Gentile showing honor to the prophet&rsquo;s servant. The newly converted Naaman is more gracious in his encounter with the greedy servant than the servant is in his exploitation of the convert. The convert who was the recipient of grace acts with the generosity the disciple lacks.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Gehazi lies to Naaman: &ldquo;My master has sent me&rdquo; — invoking Elisha&rsquo;s authority he does not have, for a need he has invented. The lie compounds the greed with false representation of the prophet. Judas: &ldquo;What will you give me if I deliver him to you?&rdquo; (Matt 26:15) — the disciple who monetizes his access to the master. The pattern of the inner-circle disciple whose proximity to the grace-giver becomes an occasion for exploitation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Naaman gives generously — two talents of silver and two changes of clothing, more than Gehazi asked. The healed man&rsquo;s generosity contrasts with the servant&rsquo;s scheme. Naaman, the recent convert, gives from gratitude; Gehazi, the long-serving insider, takes from greed. The inversion of the expected generosity-calculus.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Gehazi takes the gifts to the hill, stores them in the house, and dismisses the men who carried them. The concealment — putting the goods away before returning to Elisha — is the action of one who knows the act will not bear scrutiny. Achan after the Jericho ban (Josh 7:21: &ldquo;I saw among the spoil... I coveted them and took them... they are hidden in the earth inside my tent&rdquo;) — the pattern of the covetous theft hidden from the community.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Gehazi returns and stands before Elisha as if nothing has happened. &ldquo;Your servant has not gone anywhere.&rdquo; The lie direct — the denial of a specific action to the one who already knows. Peter before the servant girl (Mark 14:68: &ldquo;I neither know nor understand what you mean&rdquo;); Ananias and Sapphira before Peter (Acts 5:3-4: &ldquo;you have not lied to men but to God&rdquo;). The lie told to the prophet is the lie told to YHWH himself.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;Did not my heart go with you when the man stepped down from his chariot to meet you?&rdquo; — Elisha&rsquo;s prophetic knowledge encompasses what Gehazi thought was private. Then the rebuke: &ldquo;Is this a time to receive money and garments, olive orchards and vineyards, sheep and oxen, male servants and female servants?&rdquo; The expanding list of things that silver can buy — the catalogue of covetousness — shows how the first acquisition opens the imagination to all that follows. 1 Tim 6:10: &ldquo;the love of money is a root of all kinds of evil.&rdquo; Gehazi&rsquo;s single act of greed opens the door to a life organized around acquisition.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;Therefore the leprosy of Naaman shall cling to you and to your descendants forever.&rdquo; Gehazi goes out white as snow with leprosy — the disease that left Naaman transfers to the servant who profited from his healing. The judgment is exact: Gehazi exploited the grace given to a leper; now he receives the condition from which that grace had freed the Gentile. The leprosy &ldquo;forever&rdquo; (<em>lᵉʿôlām</em>) is the permanent consequence of the permanent covenant violation. The Judas parallel: &ldquo;It would have been better for that man if he had not been born&rdquo; (Matt 26:24) — the insider who exploits the master&rsquo;s gift inherits a judgment proportional to the privilege he betrayed.</p>"
  }
}

